node.title: Covid-19: 15 people have died in current Delta outbreak
node.description: Of the 15 deaths recorded by the Ministry of Health in the current outbreak, 10 were unvaccinated, two had one dose less than 14 days before they contracted Covid-19 and three were fully vaccinated.

node.title: Australia Post warns of its busiest Christmas yet as it gears up to handle record parcel demand
node.description: Australia Post warns this Christmas will be the busiest festive season on record, with parcel volumes surpassing last year's record 52 million.

node.title: SA records two positive COVID-19 cases after borders open to ACT, NSW and Victoria
node.description: Two people return positive COVID-19 tests in South Australia, the day after the state's borders opened to NSW, Victoria and the ACT.

node.title: Central Americans say poverty and food scarcity are reasons behind migration
node.description: Over 90% of the Central Americans who told researchers they wished to migrate cited unemployment, low wages, lack of money to buy food and necessities and other economic reasons.

node.title: Record Number of COVID Hospitalizations Prompts NH Gov. to Order Setup of 'Surge Centers'
node.description: Amid a spike in COVID numbers, New Hampshire Gov. Chris Sununu issued an executive order in an attempt to ease pressure on local hospitals.

node.title: Queensland paedophile gets nine years jail for Philippines offences
node.description: The 37-year-old man pled guilty to 33 charges relating to the sexual abuse of 13 children in the Philippines.

node.title: Government widens vaccine injury compensation scheme to win peace with renegade Senator
node.description: The government lowers the threshold for people to claim compensation for injury from the COVID-19 vaccine, in return for a small concession from a renegade Liberal senator who is vowing to vote against them.

node.title: New Zealand's central bank hikes rates again but Australia may not follow for years
node.description: The Reserve Bank of New Zealand raises its official cash rate for the second meeting in a row as it moves to counter surging inflation, but Australia is not in the same boat yet.

node.title: Surge of demand for NZ meat, continuing supply chain disruption predicted for 2022
node.description: Disruption that has permeated primary sectors throughout 2021 will persist next year, a report from rural lender Rabobank says.

node.title: Severe weather events mark challenging year for Tower
node.description: An increasing number of severe floods and higher building costs are reflected in the insurer's full year result.

node.title: Off-plan property buyers should insist sunset clause removed from contracts - advisor
node.description: A financial advisor says buyers of new builds can easily avoid being burnt by a sunset clause, by ensuring developers cannot benefit from it.

node.title: Dozens killed in Bulgaria bus fire, including children
node.description: At least 45 people have died after a bus crashed and caught fire in western Bulgaria, local officials say.

node.title: Body found in Clutha River confirmed to be missing Alexandra man
node.description: Police have confirmed the body located in the Clutha River last week has been identified as Central Otago man Wayne Hammond.

node.title: Elizabeth Holmes expresses some remorse during criminal trial
node.description: In her third day of testimony, Holmes acknowledged making some mistakes as CEO of Theranos.

node.title: Michigan lab behind $229 million cannabis recall sues regulators
node.description: The complaint alleges that the state's largest marijuana recall was unwarranted.

node.title: Jury Begins Deliberations in Arbery Killing
node.description: The jurors in Glynn County, Ga., will resume deliberating on Wednesday. The three men accused of killing Ahmaud Arbery face charges of both malice murder and felony murder.

node.title: Man Is Exonerated in Rape Case Described in Alice Sebold’s Memoir
node.description: Anthony J. Broadwater was convicted of the 1981 attack in Syracuse, N.Y., in a case the district attorney and a state judge agreed was flawed.

node.title: Lithuania Welcomes Belarusians as It Rebuffs Middle Easterners
node.description: People seeking asylum from repression in Belarus are processed quickly and given visas. Middle Eastern migrants passing through Belarus to the E.U. face a harsher fate.

node.title: Abraham Accords Are Changing the Middle East 'Dramatically,' Bahrain Ambassador Says
node.description: Bahrain's ambassador to the U.S. spoke with Jason Greenblatt about the Abraham Accords for a live taping of Newsweek's "The Diplomat" podcast.

node.title: Teens Accused of Killing Spanish Teacher Seek Lower Bond While Prosecutors Want It Raised
node.description: "A million dollar cash-only bond, judge, is so far unobtainable that it essentially amounts to pretrial detention without bond," said Nicole Jensen.

node.title: Pennsylvania GOP Hires Firm With No Election Experience to Perform Voting 'Investigation'
node.description: Pennsylvania Senate Republicans hired a firm to perform a "forensic investigation" of the 2020 election as Trump allies look to find first evidence of fraud.

node.title: Missouri Judge Rules Local COVID Health Orders 'Null and Void,' Should Be Ended
node.description: Judge Daniell Green said COVID health orders are in direct violation of the Missouri Constitution's separation of powers clause and are illegal.

node.title: Sister calls for royal commission into illegal robodebt scheme following suicide of brother, Corey Webb
node.description: A Port Lincoln woman is calling for a royal commission into the Government's unlawful Robodebt bungle, in response to her brother's suicide after he repaid Centrelink payments.

node.title: 'Absolutely extraordinary': Einstein's theory of relativity notes fetch $18 million at auction
node.description: Featuring endless calculations in black ink on wrinkled, lightly yellowed paper, the manuscript challenges Einstein's popular image as an absolute genius, because it shows that even he made mistakes.

node.title: NT records 11 new COVID cases, including one woman infectious in Katherine after leaving hard lockdown
node.description: The Northern Territory has recorded 11 new local cases of COVID-19 overnight, Chief Minister Michael Gunner says.

node.title: Copeton Dam in northern New South Wales fills for first time in almost a decade
node.description: A large inland dam three times the size of Sydney Harbour is full for the first time in a decade

node.title: Partying woman who sparked COVID-19 lockdown for 600,000 people fined $4,000
node.description: A 21-year-old woman is fined after she and a friend breached COVID-19 restrictions by leaving Sydney to party and shop in Newcastle, sparking the transmission of the virus to a "significant" number of people.

node.title: Peter Dutton wins defamation case over refugee advocate's 'rape apologist' tweet
node.description: Defence Minister Peter Dutton is awarded $35,000 in a defamation action against refugee advocate Shane Bazzi over a tweet which accused him of being "a rape apologist".

node.title: Concern in Napier over movements of Covid-19 case who arrived from Auckland
node.description: Napier residents are demanding health authorities be more upfront about a case of Covid-19 in the city.

node.title: Police investigating allegations of historical abuse at St Peter's School
node.description: Detective Inspector Graham Pitkethley says detectives are meeting with the schools' leadership team to discuss matters raised yesterday when alleged abuse was acknowledged and apologised for.
